'''Bob Timberlake''' is an American [[Realism (visual arts)|realist]] artist primarily known for his [[watercolor]] paintings as well as for designing and licensing lines of home furnishings, clothing and various other products. He began his career as an artist in 1970 and began his home furnishings line in 1990.<ref name="Morris">{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Ashley|title=BOB TIMBERLAKE delving into his corner of the world|url=http://www.ashleymorris.net/Uploads.html|accessdate=17 November 2011|newspaper=GS Magazine|format=PDF|month=Dec/Jan|year=2004/2005}} reprinted at www.AshleyMorris.net</ref>  He founded Linwood Furniture, LLC in 2006.<ref name="lin">[http://markets.on.nytimes.com/research/stocks/news/press_release.asp?docTag=201110251422BIZWIRE_USPRX____BW6839&feedID=600&press_symbol=176000 New York Times - Business Day]</ref>   In the fall of 2004, the Manor House Estate House at the [[Chetola Resort]] at [[Blowing Rock, North Carolina|Blowing Rock]] was renamed the ''Bob Timberlake Inn at Chetola Resort''.<ref name="inn">[http://www.chetola.com/history.html Chetola Resort History]</ref> His primary studio was created from a historic barn built in 1809 and moved to its current location in 1986.<ref name="barn">[http://www.ourstate.com/bob-timberlake Our State - Bob Timberlake<U+2019>s Lexington Landscape]</ref>

==Background==
Born in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]] on January 22, 1937 and raised in [[Lexington, North Carolina]],<ref name="Morris" /><ref name="Times-News">{{cite news|last=Apple|first=Charity|title=Celebrate '70' with Bob Timberlake|url=http://www.thetimesnews.com/articles/timberlake-3051-bob-lexington.html|accessdate=18 November 2011|newspaper=Burlington Times-News|date=14 June 2007}}</ref> Timberlake always enjoyed painting, although he didn't begin his professional career until 1970, when he was 33 years old.<ref name="clm">{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Sharon|title=A North Carolina Original: Bob Timberlake|url=http://cabarruslivingmagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/CLM-May-June-2009-Timberlake.pdf|accessdate=26 November 2011|newspaper=Cabarrus Living Magazine|format=PDF|month=May<U+2013>June|year=2009}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Industrial relations|Industrial Relations]] in 1959 from the [[University of North Carolina]]. He married in 1957 and has three children and seven grandchildren.<ref name="about">[http://www.bobtimberlake.com/biography.cfm BobTimberlake.com - About Bob]</ref>

Bob Timberlake wrote his autobiography ''Partial to Home - A Memoir of the Heart'', with fellow North Carolinian [[Jerry Bledsoe]] in 1999.<ref name="memoir">{{cite book |last1=Timberlake |first1=Bob |last2=Bledsoe |first2=Jerry |title=Partial to Home: A Memoir of the Heart |publisher=John F Blair Pub |year=1999 |isbn=978-1-878086-81-5}}</ref>  In it he reveals that he was a self-taught artist influenced and mentored by [[Andrew Wyeth]].  Timberlake came home one night when he was 28, and upon reading an article and viewing photographs of Wyeth's work in [[Life (magazine)|Life magazine]], was "moved to tears" and was convinced that he too was destined to become a painter. He began his career shortly thereafter.<ref name="memoir"/>

== Furnishings ==
Timberlake first designed and made a [[Chest of drawers|dresser]] when he was 14 and 15 which took him 350 hours to complete. [[Ford Motor Company]] selected Timberlake's work as "representative of youth in the 1950s".<ref>Craver, Richard. "[http://www2.journalnow.com/news/2012/jan/22/wsmain01-painter-furniture-designer-and-entreprene-ar-1841731/ At 75, Timberlake still full of designs]". ''Winston-Salem Journal'', January 22, 2012. p. A8.</ref>

Timberlake partnered with Lexington Furniture (later renamed to Lexington Home Brands) to create ''The World of Bob Timberlake'', which became the best-selling furniture collection in industry history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Craver|first=Richard|title=Designer will end ties with company|url=http://www2.journalnow.com/business/2010/dec/13/designer-will-end-ties-with-company-ar-612065/|accessdate=18 November 2011|newspaper=Winston-Salem Journal|date=12 December 2010}}</ref> The ''Bob Timberlake'' brand includes a range of furniture styles, including Eighteenth century, Arts and Crafts, and English and Irish cottage.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}

== Postage stamps ==
Bob has designed three different postage stamps for the [[United States Postal Service]], including a 15 cent stamp titled ''Wreath and Toys'' issued on Oct. 31, 1980, which was based on antique toys in artist Bob Timberlake<U+2019>s collection. ([[Scott catalogue]] number 1843),<ref name="postal">[http://about.usps.com/who-we-are/postal-history/christmas-stamps-2010.htm USPS Christmas Holiday Stamps]</ref> as well as the 1988 North Carolina Statehood stamp, and 1989 South Carolina Statehood stamp.<ref name="clm" />

==Galleries==
There are two Timberlake galleries, including one located in at 1714 East Center Street Extension in [[Lexington, North Carolina]]. The other is located at 946 Main Street in [[Blowing Rock, North Carolina]].  The galleries offer original and signed [[lithograph]]ed artwork by Timberlake, as well as home furnishings and other items created or designed by him and licensed by various manufacturers.<ref name="about" />{{third-party-inline|date=December 2011}}

==Exhibitions==
His first [[art exhibition]] was a sold-out show in May 1970 in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]].<ref name="Morris" />

In 1973, he held the first of seven one-person exhibits at [[Hammer Galleries]] in [[New York, New York|New York City]]. The first show was sold 
out before it opened, the first time this had ever happened for this well established gallery.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}

Along with [[Norman Rockwell]], he exhibited at the [[Artists of America]] show in 1974, at the Franklin Center in Philadelphia and in New Jersey.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}

In 1998, Timberlake painted "White House Christmas" for the exhibition "White House Impressions: The President's House Through the Eye of the Artist." He was one of only 14 artists chosen to depict the [[White House]] for the exhibition sponsored by the [[White House Historical Association]]. It has been exhibited in the White House and in several [[Presidential library|presidential libraries]].<ref name="clintonlibrary">{{cite news|last=Knopfler|first=Vicki|title=Clinton Library exhibit gets Tarheel touch|accessdate=18 November 2011|newspaper=High Point Enterprise|date=1 February 2007}}</ref> 

In 2007, in celebration of his 70th birthday, the Bob Timberlake Gallery featured an exhibit of 70 pieces spanning his career.<ref name="Times-News" />

==Awards and honors==
[[File:Bob Timberlake Freeway sign.jpg|right|thumb|200px|A section of [[Interstate 85]] near exit 96 in North Carolina has been designated as the Bob Timberlake Freeway]]
* 1978 - He was recognized by then [[President of the United States|President]] [[Jimmy Carter]] for his work with [[Keep America Beautiful]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}  Three years earlier, he had been named ''The Official Artist of Keep America Beautiful, lnc.'' and the official spokesperson for Keep America Beautiful.
* 1978 <U+2013> He received the [[North Carolina Award|North Carolina Public Service Award]].
* 1979 <U+2013> He received an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Degree]] for Doctor of [[Humanities]] [[Honoris Causa]] from [[High Point University]].
* 1981 <U+2013> Was officially recognized by then current President [[Ronald Reagan]], along with [[Iron Eyes Cody]] and the Keep America Beautiful organization during an [[Oval Office]] ceremony.
* 1987 <U+2013> Honored by the [[North Carolina]] [[Cystic Fibrosis Foundation]] and the [[Duke University]] Comprehensive Cancer Center for his [[humanitarian]] service, which have so far raised over $7.3 million (as of 2009) by the sale of his donated artwork.
* 1989 <U+2013> Received the [[Albert Schweitzer Prize for Humanitarianism]] for Artistry.<ref name="starnews">[http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1454&dat=19890305&id=YFFIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RRQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2442,1737502 Ben Steelman, Star News Sunday, March 5, 1989]</ref>
* 1989 <U+2013> [[Duke University]] Comprehensive Cancer Center awarded him the Shingleton Award for his support.
* 1995 <U+2013> Was given a distinguished alumni award from the [[University of North Carolina]] at Chapel Hill.
* 1998 <U+2013> Was honored as the [[North Carolina Press Association]]<U+2019>s [[North Carolinian of the Year]] in [[Pinehurst, North Carolina|Pinehurst, NC]].
* 2002 <U+2013> Received an Honorary Doctor of Humanities from [[Methodist University|Methodist College]], [[Fayetteville, North Carolina|Fayetteville, NC]]
* 2006 <U+2013> Awarded the [[Order of the Long Leaf Pine]],<ref name="longleaf">{{cite news|last=Beckwith|first=Ryan Teague|title=What is the Order of the Long Leaf Pine?|url=http://projects.newsobserver.com/faq/what_is_the_order_of_the_long_leaf_pine|accessdate=11 November 2011|newspaper=Raleigh News & Observer|date=26 June 2007}}</ref> North Carolina<U+2019>s highest civilian honor.

